ce:section.ce:para:
The response between N- CQDs nanoprobe and Hg(II) was investigated under the optimum experimental conditions. As shown in Fig. 7, the fluorescence intensity gradually decreased with the increasing Hg(II) concentrations from 15 to 104 nM. The fluorescence quenching value showed a linear relationship with Hg(II) concentration. The fitting equation was described as: Y = 275.8 × lgX − 226.4, R2 = 0.9856 (ΔF = F0 – F, F0
                         and F represent the fluorescence intensity of N-CQDs nanoprobe before and after adding Hg(II), respectively). According to the principle of S/N = 3, the limit of detection (LOD) was calculated to be 8 nM. Compared with previous literatures (Table 2
                        ), the N-CQDs nanoprobe based on a joint of dynamic and static quenching in this study had a wider detection range and higher sensitivity for Hg(II) detection.
